    <h2>Track Details</h2>
    <p>
        <p><b>1.1 - What's Next: Coming face-to-face with designers shaping the future of games.</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 10, 9:30 AM - 11:00 AM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">The ongoing conversation about the best use of Hollywood licenses or the importance of a game's soundtrack may qualify as today's big-buzz topics, but addressing the opportunities and challenges facing today's game industry is only half the story. What about upcoming games that go beyond today's trends and prosaic preoccupations? What's next? What's <i> really</i> next? This session will invite designers who have already made an impact on game design today to share their personal vision of tomorrow's game experience and what they are doing to shape it. What new concepts are they working with? What's their idea of perfect gameplay? What should tomorrow's games aspire to? And what chances need to be taken to get there?&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator/Panelist:</td><td class="tableRowEven">David Perry, Executive Video Game Industry Consultant - GameConsultants.com&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Todd Howard, Executive Producer - Bethesda Game Studios<br>Ken Levine, President and Co-founder - Irrational Games<br>51 Suda, CEO, Game Designer, Director, Scenario Writer - grasshopper manufacture<br>Tim Willits, Co-Owner and Lead Designer of Doom 3 - id Software, Inc.<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>1.2 - The inner game: What goes into the industry's best-selling titles</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 10, 11:30 AM - 1:00 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">What are the critical elements that drive a game to the top of the sales charts? Is it a recognizable IP? Great gameplay? Innovative features? Technology bells and whistles? A perfectly paced learning curve? Some games that seemed to "have it all" and were released to high scores from reviewers bombed on the sales charts. On the other hand, some games that missed their marks and received dismal ratings have turned out to be blockbuster chart movers. How can those facts be explained? What can be more important than exceptional gameplay and a great feature set? This session will focus on the real-world factors that influence sales. How do recognizable IPs help capture a wider audience? How important is balanced gameplay that challenges core gamers as well as entertains the mass market? What learning curve is the perfect learning curve? How much outside talent is necessary, and how do you manage it appropriately? Accomplished designers discuss how they prioritized these criteria, why they decided to include some and not others, and how their decision s affected sales.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Eric Zimmerman, Co-Founder and CEO - Gamelab&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Louis Castle, Vice President, Creative Development - Electronic Arts - Los Angeles<br>Kelly Flock, Executive Vice President of Worldwide Publishing - THQ, Inc.<br>Julien Gerighty, Senior Producer - Ubisoft Shanghai (Splinter Cell Double Agent)<br>Tetsuya Mizuguchi, Chief Creative Officer - Q Entertainment (Meteos, Lumines)<br>Peter Molyneux, Managing Director - Lionhead Studios (The Movies)<br>Richard Rouse, III, Director of Game Design - Midway Games (The Suffering)<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>1.3 - Sneak Peeks: Behind the scenes of Metal Gear Solid 4, Gears of War and Red Steel</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 10, 1:30 PM - 3:00 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Last year, attendees were given an insider's view of Ubisoft's King Kong, Activision's Call of Duty 2, and The Godfather from Electronic Arts. Design leads from each team showed never-before-seen game assets and addressed the specific challenges encountered during their game's development. This year, we will present an exclusive look at three top games still in the production pipeline. Listen in as project leads discuss how they manage the game development process and how they cope with the needs of their team, their publisher, and the media. Come prepared to learn how the designers and project managers for these games handle the pressures of developing a triple-A, big-budget title.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Geoff Keighley, Contributing Writer - Business 2.0&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Cliff Bleszinski, Lead Designer - Epic Games (Presenting Gears of War)<br>Hideo Kojima, Director of Kojima Productions (Presenting Metal Gear Solid 4; PlayStation 3 - Konami<br>Xavier Poix, Managing Director - Ubisoft Montpellier and Paris Studios (Presenting Red Steel, a Nintendo Revolution exclusive)<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>1.4 - Franchise power: Understanding the DNA of the industry's greatest games</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 10, 3:30 PM - 5:00 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Creating a single blockbuster title is hard enough, but creating a game that can spawn an ongoing series is doubly hard. For every Need for Speed and Grand Theft Auto, there's a one-shot wonder that died after the first iteration or sequel. What separates games that have franchise potential from those that can't endure even a single update? What is it about a game's characters, world, set of challenges, or reward system that gives it franchise legs? And is there a downside to annualizing a title year after year? This session will look at four of the most significant franchises of the past decade and will determine the key elements behind their success. How was their superstar status maintained over the course of years, through platform updates and generational shifts among gamers? How was feature innovation used to maintain a game's relevance with consumers? In what ways can sequels enable innovation, giving designers their best opportunity for showcasing a killer app? Hear key members of each game's design team share their unique recipe for creating games that remain top sellers release after release.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Jeff Green, Editor-in-Chief, Computer Gaming World - Ziff Davis&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Ed Boon, Creative Director - Midway Games (Mortal Kombat)<br>Grant Collier, President - Infinity Ward (Call of Duty series)<br>Soren Johnson, Designer and Programmer - Firaxis Games (Civilization IV)<br>Hanno Lemke, Vice President, General Manager - Electronic Arts Black Box  (Need for Speed series)<br>Yannis Mallat, Chief Executive Officer - Ubisoft Montreal (Prince of Persia series)<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>1.5 - Cracking the code of creativity: Drawing novelty, awe, and adventure from traditional genres.</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 11, 9:30 AM - 11:00 AM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">What does it take to work <i>within</I> a popular genre but <i>outside</i> the boundaries of expectation? Is creativity really as absent from the current generation of games as many claim? This year, a number of titles answered industry critics and proved that originality in game design is limited only by a designer's intelligence, inspiration, and imagination. God of War, Project Assassins, Guitar Hero, and Spore, working within the long-established genres of action adventure, rhythm/music, and simulation confirm that faithfulness to genre, rather then limiting game design, can be fertile ground for creativity and evolution. This session invites designers to discuss how they took shop worn genres to new heights--by perfecting the wheel rather than reinventing it.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">N'Gai Croal, General Editor, Technology - Newsweek&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Cory Barlog, Game Director - Sony Computer Entertainment America (God of War)<br>Lucy Bradshaw, Vice President - Executive Producer - Electronic Arts (Spore)<br>Patrice Desilets, Creative Director - Ubisoft Montreal (Project Assassins)<br>Rob Kay, Lead Designer - Harmonix (Guitar Hero)<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>1.6 - Massively cross-platform: Closing in on the dream of one game, many platforms</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 11, 11:30 AM - 1:00 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">For years, developers, publishers, and gamers have talked about getting game terminals talking to each other, regardless of their platform. While not easy, opening up a single, persistent gameworld to PC, console, and portable gamers is now within reach. Taking the first real steps was Final Fantasy XI, which linked PlayStation 2 and PC gamers. Recently, that title opened its gameworld to Xbox 360 gamers as well. While FFXI may have been the first title to offer this level of cross-platform gaming, it won't be the last. Developers are designing the infrastructure that will link gamers on home terminals seamlessly with each other as well as with gamers on the go. This session will focus on where the industry stands today in enabling massively cross-platform (MCP) games. What are the remaining technical challenges? How will MCP games change the consumer experience? And how will MCP games alter the relationship between the publisher, developer, and platform owner? Hear how designers, publishers, and technologists are preparing for MCP games, and find out how soon they will become the norm.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Jessica Mulligan, Author/Consultant - &nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Laura Fryer, Director Advance Technology Group - Microsoft Game Studies<br>Richard Garriott, Executive Producer - NCsoft<br>Ichiro Otobe, Chief Strategist - Square Enix Co., Ltd<br>John Smedley, President - Sony Online Entertainment<br>Mike Yuen, Senior Director, Gaming Group - QUALCOMM Internet Services<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>1.7 - Perfecting the mix of story, character development, and interactivity</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 11, 1:30 PM - 3:00 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">An exciting line in the history of game development has been crossed. After years of dialogue and ongoing attempts to deepen plot, build believable characters, and refine programming skills, game designers are now creating interactive experiences that rival a movie's level of depth and engagement. Can a game make you cry? Can it make you believe in a character's mission, in a character's struggle, strengths, weaknesses, and values? Through the inclusion of story specialists--actors, screenwriters, editors, and special-effects experts--games have made spectacular leaps in delivering an immersive experience. The industry's top designers will share the podium with crossover talent from a variety of entertainment arts as they discuss how to create a game that can hold a player's attention for ten to fifty hours, how they invest game characters with emotion, passion, and intelligence, how they build heartbreak, joy, and fear into the story, and what genres are needed in a single title to deliver a satisfying and complete experience.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Ian Lane Davis, Ph.D., CEO and Founder - Mad Doc Software, LLC (Empire Earth 2)&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">David Cage, CEO and Founder - Quantic Dream (Indigo Prophecy)<br>Richard Dansky, Central Clancy Writer/Manager of Design - Ubisoft/Red Storm Entertainment<br>David Jaffe, Game Director - Sony Computer Entertainment America (God of War)<br>Marc Laidlaw, Writer/Game Designer - Valve Software (Half-Life, Half-Life 2)<br>Neil Young, Vice President, General Manager - Electronic Arts - Los Angeles<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>1.8 - How mobile game creators are using high-speed networks and high-end handsets to make wireless games better</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 11, 3:30 PM - 5:00 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Mobile game developers have dreamed large for years. 3D graphics, real-time multiplayer gaming, and mobile titles that connect with the bigger worlds of PC and console games are just a few of the blue-sky ambitions designers have been tracking since the early days of Snake. Now, as data transmission speeds and handset specs climb, many of these dreams are within reach. What technologies are enabling mobile game designers to unleash their imaginations on the almost half a billion mobile gamers worldwide? What does increased CDMA and 3G coverage mean for game creators? What are the most creative games under development that use 3G technology? What is the state of creative and original game development using J2ME and BREW-enabled handsets today? Where are we in the transition from 2D to 3D in mobile? With the combined European and US mobile markets predicted to drive $2.4 billion in revenue by 2008, knowing the upper limits of technology will help you squeeze the maximum creativity from wireless handsets and increase your chances for success in the mobile game marketplace.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Julie Ask, Research Director and Senior Analyst - Jupiter Research&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Eric Albert, Head of North American Operations - Gameloft<br>Kyu C. Lee, President - GAMEVIL, Inc.<br>Robert Nashak, Sr. VP, Chief Creative Officer - Glu Mobile<br>Eberhard Schoneburg, Chairman, Chief Executive Officer - Artificial Life (V-girl)<br>Lincoln Wallen, Chief Technology Officer - Electronic Arts Mobile<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br />
